Following the given logic rules and using 0-ary predicates, I will symbolize the given propositions:

[
[F(2) & G(2)];
[G(2) ⇒ ∼G(4)];
[G(6) ⇒ (G(2) & ∼G(3) & ∼G(4) & ∼G(5))];
[∼G(6) ⇒ G(4)]
]

Explanation:

1. "2 is an even prime number" is represented by F(2) & G(2).
2. "If 2 is prime, then 4 is not prime" is represented by G(2) ⇒ ∼G(4).
3. "Only 2 is prime, for 6 to be prime" means if 6 is prime, then 2 is prime and 3, 4, and 5 are not prime. This is represented by G(6) ⇒ (G(2) & ∼G(3) & ∼G(4) & ∼G(5)).
4. "Unless 6 is prime, 4 is prime" is equivalent to "If 6 is not prime, then 4 is prime", which is represented by ∼G(6) ⇒ G(4).

These propositions use 0-ary predicates as they involve specific numbers rather than variables.

